node.text:
Here's to us! 🥂 September is our month to celebrate our accomplishments, remember our loved ones who gained their wings, and to educate and raise awareness to those around us about sickle cell. ⁠
⁠
Happy Sickle Cell Awareness Month!! 🎉⁠
⁠
This month we listened to you all and created a campaign we hope you will find useful in helping you manage sickle cell disease. It's called Tools in the SCD Toolbox: Treatment Options for Sickle Cell Disease.⁠
⁠
We are breaking down global treatment options available for us and sharing the benefits of each treatment option. ⁠
⁠
We also want to hear from you. How do you manage your #sicklecell disease? ⁠
⁠
Please share the message far and wide that September is Sickle Cell Awareness month, and stay tuned for what we have for you all. We're excited to bring this information to the community in hopes to have an ever better informed community and for you to know what options are available to manage sickle cell disease. ⁠
⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecellawarenessmonth #NSCAM21

node.text:
We at #SickleCell101 are collaborating with Klein Buendel to identify teens who can help with the development of Pinpoint, an app that helps young sickle cell patients assess and talk about their pain with their parents and healthcare providers.

To see if you are eligible to participate, visit scdstudies.com/featured/pinpoint (link in bio) to learn more PINPOINT and help contribute to research for sickle cell. Don’t forget to also share this with any other individuals who can also participate in this survey.

More about this study

Pain, which is the hallmark symptom of sickle cell disease (SCD), is also the most common clinical problem associated with SCD-related hospital admissions in children living with sickle cell disease.
Yet programs to assist children and adolescents with better identification and communication of their pain are lacking. 

Pinpoint is a phone and tablet app that uses interactive games to help teens learn how to communicate their sickle cell disease. Research shows that interactive gaming technology can enhance adolescents' learning and can be especially effective in delivering health-related messages and tools to improve self-care. The goal of this study is to develop a final, effective version of the Pinpoint app. We are looking for teens, ages 13-17 years old to participate in this virtual research study and assist with the development of Pinpoint. This project is approved by the Western Institutional Review Board and funded by the National Institute on Minority Health & Health Disparities, a part of the National Institutes of Health (Grant Number: R44 MD010746). 

Visit our patient-friendly research platform, Sickle Cell Studies to learn more about the Pinpoint Study and help contribute to research for sickle cell.

#sicklecell

node.text:
Get into this study about sickle cell and nutrition 😳 It seriously makes you rethink not eating your fruits and veggies 🥦⁠
⁠
This study shows there is a correlation between diet and our experience with sickle cell disease. We now know that there are preventative dietary methods we can use to help us manage sickle cell disease. ⁠
⁠
One of these studies explains how deficiencies in micronutrients (vitamins and minerals) and macronutrients (proteins, fats, and carbs) can lead to more complications in sickle cell disease. Did you know this? 🤔⁠
⁠
What does that mean? It means it’s very important to make sure we eat plenty of nutritious foods so that our bodies have what they need to function well. Without the necessary nutrients, our bodies with sickle cell disease struggle to meet the many demands and lead to pain, reduced growth and development, vaso-occlusive crises, hospitalizations, and many other complications and symptoms.⁠
⁠
For the full study for the sickle cell nerds, the link is in the stories!⁠

Source: Influence of Nutrition on Disease Severity and Health-related Quality of Life in Adults with Sickle Cell Disease: A Prospective Study; Sanaa Kamal, et al.

⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecell #nutritionforsicklecell #sicklecellwarrior #sicklecellawareness⁠

node.text:
What nutritious 🥬 meals do you prepare for #sicklecell?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Sometimes the hardest part is deciding what to prepare, blocking time to cook or prep, what foods to pair together to get all of the nutrients, or ensuring that you actually enjoy what you prepare. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
We provide some examples of meals for you to try out! ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Also, notice that many of the foods listed are repeats, many they contain multiple necessary nutrients, like green, leafy vegetables, nuts and seeds, and citrus fruits. This makes choosing foods easier, knowing that you get a lot of what you need from one food. This is why it’s important to eat a balanced, nutritious diet.⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
How many of these do you incorporate into your diet?🥦

What we eat affects how often we experience complications. A nutritious diet really supports good health and replenishes all of the nutrients it loses from removing broken down red blood cells and creating new ones. Remember, sickled red blood cells last between 10 and 20 days, while typical red blood cells last 120. That’s quite a difference and the comparison shows how much our body has to work to create new red blood cells as quickly as possible. THAT TAKES ENERGY.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
That is why individuals with sickle cell disease are (well, should be) strongly advised to eat a balanced, nutrient-dense diet, especially one that: ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
- Contains enough protein (for individuals with SCD without kidney damage or disease, protein intake is recommended at 30-35% of total calories per day depending on each person and physical activity level)⁠⁠
High in calories (from nutritious foods)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
- Contains a variety of fruits and vegetables for necessary vitamins and minerals⁠⁠
⁠⁠
- Contains more whole grain carbs than processed or “white” carbs⁠⁠
⁠⁠
- Includes good sources of monounsaturated (like nuts and avocados) and polyunsaturated fats (like omega 3’s from salmon or olive oil)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Even with all of this, there are specific nutrients those with SCD should pay great attention to. Check out the image above and let us know: have you heard recommendations of these nutrients?⁠⁠

More often than not, recommending folate/folic acid and drinking lots of water is as far as many healthcare providers will say about nutrition or our dietary needs. ⁠

While there are a number of reasons for the gap, us with sickle cell are the ones experiencing the effect of that knowledge gap. There are many other dietary needs for sickle cell disease outside of folate and water.⁠
⁠
Nutrition often is a self-exploration project. We are using this month to educate about nutrients needed for #sicklecell and what foods to eat to get those nutrients.⁠

node.text:
SCT is the most common hemoglobin mutation in the world yet most individuals are unaware of their genotype and not educated about potential complications that can be associated with SCT. Although most individuals with SCT typically experience little to no complications, some of the complications that can occur like exercise-induced muscle breakdown (rhabdomyolysis), heat stroke and renal medullary carcinoma can be fatal if untreated quickly.

All individuals with SCT are encouraged to educate their health care providers about their SCT status and discuss any concerns they might have relating to potential complications. 

Here are some tips to consider if you have sickle cell trait: 

For athletes, always hydrate and warm up before intense activities. Inform your coaches quickly if you have any unusual symptoms than what you are used to.

If an individual with SCT is being diagnosed with diabetes ensure your health care provide is aware of your sickle cell trait genotype to ensure the proper test is used to evaluate your Hemoglobin A1c (diabetes test).

For the sickle cell nerds: According to the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Disease, the hemoglobin A1C assay may be unreliable for diagnosing and monitoring diabetes and prediabetes in individuals with SCT or other hemoglobinopathies.
